    {
      "content": "Work with a JavaScript backend mobile service",
      "pos": [
        28,
        73
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Provides examples on how to define, register, and use server scripts in Azure Mobile Services.",
      "pos": [
        93,
        187
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Work with a JavaScript backend mobile service",
      "pos": [
        521,
        566
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article provides detailed information about and examples of how to work with a JavaScript backend in Azure Mobile Services.",
      "pos": [
        568,
        696
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        701,
        733
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"intro\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Introduction"
    },
    {
      "content": "In a JavaScript backend mobile service, you can define custom business logic as JavaScript code that's stored and executed on the server.",
      "pos": [
        735,
        872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This server script code is assigned to one of the following server functions:",
      "pos": [
        873,
        950
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[Insert, read, update, or delete operations on a given table][Table operations].",
      "pos": [
        954,
        1034
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[Scheduled jobs][Job Scheduler].",
      "pos": [
        1037,
        1069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[HTTP methods defined in a custom API][Custom API anchor].",
      "pos": [
        1072,
        1130
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The signature of the main function in the server script depends on the context of where the script is used.",
      "pos": [
        1133,
        1240
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also define common script code as nodes.js modules that are shared across scripts.",
      "pos": [
        1241,
        1331
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Source control and shared code][Source control, shared code, and helper functions].",
      "pos": [
        1332,
        1442
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1444,
        1558
      ],
      "content": "For descriptions of individual server script objects and functions, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Mobile Services server script reference]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1564,
        1608
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"table-scripts\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Table operations"
    },
    {
      "content": "A table operation script is a server script that is registered to an operation on a table&amp;mdash;insert, read, update, or delete (<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>del<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        1610,
        1746
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes how to work with table operations in a JavaScript backend, which includes the following sections:",
      "pos": [
        1747,
        1867
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[Overview of table operations][Basic table operations]",
      "pos": [
        1871,
        1925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Register for table operations]",
      "pos": [
        1928,
        1967
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Override the default response]",
      "pos": [
        1970,
        2009
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Override execute success]",
      "pos": [
        2012,
        2046
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Override default error handling]",
      "pos": [
        2049,
        2090
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How to: Generate unique ID values",
      "pos": [
        2094,
        2127
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Add custom parameters]",
      "pos": [
        2148,
        2179
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Work with table users][How to: Work with users]",
      "pos": [
        2182,
        2238
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2243,
        2301
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"basic-table-ops\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Overview of table operations"
    },
    {
      "content": "The name of the script must match the kind of operation for which it is registered.",
      "pos": [
        2303,
        2386
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only one script can be registered for a given table operation.",
      "pos": [
        2387,
        2449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The script is executed every time that the given operation is invoked by a REST request&amp;mdash;for example, when a POST request is received to insert an item into the table.",
      "pos": [
        2450,
        2622
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services does not preserve state between script executions.",
      "pos": [
        2623,
        2689
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because a new global context is created every time a script is run, any state variables that are defined in the script are reinitialized.",
      "pos": [
        2690,
        2827
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to store state from one request to another, create a table in your mobile service, and then read and write the state to the table.",
      "pos": [
        2828,
        2970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [How to: Access tables from scripts].",
      "pos": [
        2971,
        3034
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You write table operation scripts if you need to enforce customized business logic when the operation is executed.",
      "pos": [
        3036,
        3150
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the following script rejects insert operations where the string length of the <ph id=\"ph1\">`text`</ph> field is greater than ten characters:",
      "pos": [
        3151,
        3286
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A table script function always takes three arguments.",
      "pos": [
        3552,
        3605
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first argument varies depending on the table operation.",
      "pos": [
        3609,
        3668
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For inserts and updates, it is an <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>item<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> object, which is a JSON representation of the row being affected by the operation.",
      "pos": [
        3677,
        3802
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This allows you to access column values by name, for example, <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>item.Owner<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, where <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Owner<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> is one of the names in the JSON representation.",
      "pos": [
        3803,
        3940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a delete, it is the ID of the record to delete.",
      "pos": [
        3947,
        3998
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4006,
        4081
      ],
      "content": "And for a read, it is a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">query object]</ept> that specifies the rowset to return."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4085,
        4196
      ],
      "content": "The second argument is always a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>user object<ept id=\"p1\">][User object]</ept> that represents the user that submitted the request."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4201,
        4371
      ],
      "content": "The third argument is always a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>request object<ept id=\"p1\">][request object]</ept>, by which you can control execution of the requested operation and the response that's sent to the client."
    },
    {
      "content": "Here are the canonical main-function signatures for the table operations:",
      "pos": [
        4373,
        4446
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4451,
        4525
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Insert<ept id=\"p1\">][insert function]</ept>: <ph id=\"ph1\">`function insert (item, user, request) { ... }`</ph>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4528,
        4602
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Update<ept id=\"p1\">][update function]</ept>: <ph id=\"ph1\">`function update (item, user, request) { ... }`</ph>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4605,
        4674
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Delete<ept id=\"p1\">][delete function]</ept>: <ph id=\"ph1\">`function del (id, user, request) { ... }`</ph>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4677,
        4746
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Read<ept id=\"p1\">][read function]</ept>: <ph id=\"ph1\">`function read (query, user, request) { ... }`</ph>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4749,
        4885
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>A function that's registered to the delete operation must be named <bpt id=\"p1\">_</bpt>del<ept id=\"p1\">_</ept> because delete is a reserved keyword in JavaScript."
    },
    {
      "content": "Every server script has a main function, and may have optional helper functions.",
      "pos": [
        4888,
        4968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Even though a server script may have been been created for a specific table, it can also reference other tables in the same database.",
      "pos": [
        4969,
        5102
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also define common functions as modules that can be shared across scripts.",
      "pos": [
        5103,
        5185
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Source control and shared code][Source control, shared code, and helper functions].",
      "pos": [
        5186,
        5296
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5301,
        5368
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"register-table-scripts\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Register table scripts"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can define server scripts that are registered to a table operation in one of the following ways:",
      "pos": [
        5370,
        5470
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Management Portal<ept id=\"p1\">][Management Portal]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5474,
        5526
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scripts for table operations are accessed in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Scripts<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab for a given table.",
      "pos": [
        5527,
        5610
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following shows the default code registered to the insert script for the <ph id=\"ph1\">`TodoItem`</ph> table.",
      "pos": [
        5611,
        5705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can override this code with your own custom business logic.",
      "pos": [
        5706,
        5769
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![1][1]",
      "pos": [
        5775,
        5782
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5792,
        5891
      ],
      "content": "To learn how to do this, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Validate and modify data in Mobile Services by using server scripts]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "By using source control.",
      "pos": [
        5897,
        5921
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you have source control enabled, simply create a file named <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;em&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">`&lt;table&gt;`</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;/em&gt;</ph>.<ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;em&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph5\">`&lt;operation&gt;`</ph><ph id=\"ph6\">&lt;/em&gt;</ph>.js in the .\\service\\table subfolder in your git repository, where <ph id=\"ph7\">&lt;em&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph8\">`&lt;table&gt;`</ph><ph id=\"ph9\">&lt;/em&gt;</ph> is the name of the table and <ph id=\"ph10\">&lt;em&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph11\">`&lt;operation&gt;`</ph><ph id=\"ph12\">&lt;/em&gt;</ph> is the table operation being registered.",
      "pos": [
        5922,
        6206
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Source control and shared code][Source control, shared code, and helper functions].",
      "pos": [
        6207,
        6317
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From the command prompt by using the Azure command line tool.",
      "pos": [
        6321,
        6382
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Using the command line tool].",
      "pos": [
        6383,
        6439
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6442,
        6590
      ],
      "content": "A table operation script must call at least one of the following functions of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">request object]</ept> to make sure that the client receives a response."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6596,
        6696
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute function<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The operation is completed as requested and the standard response is returned."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6701,
        6753
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>respond function<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: A custom response is returned."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6757,
        6900
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.IMPORTANT]</ph> When a script has a code path in which neither <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> nor <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> is invoked, the operation may become unresponsive."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6902,
        7009
      ],
      "content": "The following script calls the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function to complete the data operation requested by the client:"
    },
    {
      "content": "In this example, the item is inserted into the database and the appropriate status code is returned to the user.",
      "pos": [
        7091,
        7203
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function is called, the <ph id=\"ph1\">`item`</ph>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>query<ept id=\"p2\">][query object]</ept>, or <ph id=\"ph2\">`id`</ph> value that was passed as the first argument into the script function is used to perform the operation.",
      "pos": [
        7206,
        7392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For an insert, update or query operation, you can modify the item or query before you call <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>:",
      "pos": [
        7393,
        7496
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8060,
        8185
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>In a delete script, changing the value of the supplied userId variable does not affect which record gets deleted."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8187,
        8274
      ],
      "content": "For more examples, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Read and write data]</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">Modify the request]</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p3\">Validate data]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8280,
        8349
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"override-response\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Override the default response"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also use a script to implement validation logic that can override the default response behavior.",
      "pos": [
        8351,
        8455
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If validation fails, just call the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function instead of the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> function and write the response to the client:",
      "pos": [
        8456,
        8585
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this example, the request is rejected when the inserted item does not have a <ph id=\"ph1\">`userId`</ph> property that matches the <ph id=\"ph2\">`userId`</ph> of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">user object]</ept> that's supplied for the authenticated client.",
      "pos": [
        8853,
        9043
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, a database operation (<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>insert<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>) does not occur, and a response that has a 403 HTTP status code and a custom error message is returned to the client.",
      "pos": [
        9044,
        9206
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more examples, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Modify the response]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9207,
        9252
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        9257,
        9320
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"override-success\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Override execute success"
    },
    {
      "content": "By default in a table operation, the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function writes responses automatically.",
      "pos": [
        9322,
        9411
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, you can pass two optional parameters to the execute function that override its behavior on success and/or on error.",
      "pos": [
        9412,
        9536
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By passing in a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>success<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> handler when you call execute, you can modify the results of a query before you write them to the response.",
      "pos": [
        9538,
        9673
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following example calls <ph id=\"ph1\">`execute({ success: function(results) { ... })`</ph> to perform additional work after data is read from the database but before the response is written:",
      "pos": [
        9674,
        9849
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you provide a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>success<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> handler to the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> function, you must also call the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> function as part of the <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>success<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> handler so that the runtime knows that the script has completed and that a response can be written.",
      "pos": [
        10211,
        10449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you call <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> without passing any arguments, Mobile Services generates the default response.",
      "pos": [
        10450,
        10554
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        10558,
        10695
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>You can call <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> without arguments to invoke the default response only after you first call the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> function."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        10701,
        10769
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"override-error\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Override default error handling"
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function can fail if there is a loss of connectivity to the database, an invalid object, or an incorrect query.",
      "pos": [
        10771,
        10898
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default when an error occurs, server scripts log the error and write an error result to the response.",
      "pos": [
        10899,
        11003
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because Mobile Services provides default error handling, you don't have to handle errors that may occur in the service.",
      "pos": [
        11004,
        11123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can override the default error handling by implementing explicit error handling if you want a particular compensating action or when you want to use the global console object to write more detailed information to the log.",
      "pos": [
        11126,
        11351
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do this by supplying an <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>error<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> handler to the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>execute<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> function:",
      "pos": [
        11352,
        11422
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11643,
        11759
      ],
      "content": "When you provide an error handler, Mobile Services returns an error result to the client when <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>respond<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is called."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11761,
        11838
      ],
      "content": "You can also provide both a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>success<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and an <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>error<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> handler if you wish."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11843,
        11905
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"generate-guids\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Generate unique ID values"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services supports unique custom string values for the table's <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>id<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> column.",
      "pos": [
        11907,
        11990
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This allows applications to use custom values such as email addresses or user names for the ID.",
      "pos": [
        11991,
        12086
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "String IDs provide you with the following benefits:",
      "pos": [
        12089,
        12140
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IDs are generated without making a round-trip to the database.",
      "pos": [
        12144,
        12206
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Records are easier to merge from different tables or databases.",
      "pos": [
        12209,
        12272
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IDs values can integrate better with an application's logic.",
      "pos": [
        12275,
        12335
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a string ID value is not set on an inserted records, Mobile Services generates a unique value for the ID.",
      "pos": [
        12337,
        12447
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can generate your own unique ID values in server scripts.",
      "pos": [
        12448,
        12509
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The script example below generates a custom GUID and assigns it to a new record's ID.",
      "pos": [
        12510,
        12595
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is similar to the id value that Mobile Services would generate if you didn't pass in a value for a record's ID.",
      "pos": [
        12596,
        12712
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When an application provides a value for an ID, Mobile Services stores it as-is.",
      "pos": [
        13243,
        13323
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This includes leading or trailing white spaces.",
      "pos": [
        13324,
        13371
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "White space are not trimmed from value.",
      "pos": [
        13372,
        13411
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13413,
        13510
      ],
      "content": "The value for the <ph id=\"ph1\">`id`</ph> must be unique and it must not include characters from the following sets:"
    },
    {
      "content": "Control characters: [0x0000-0x001F] and [0x007F-0x009F].",
      "pos": [
        13514,
        13570
      ]
