      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        20811,
        20870
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"handle-methods\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Implement HTTP methods"
    },
    {
      "content": "A custom API can handle one or more of the HTTP methods, GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE.",
      "pos": [
        20872,
        20963
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An exported function is defined for each HTTP method handled by the custom API.",
      "pos": [
        20964,
        21043
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A single custom API code file can export one or all of the following functions:",
      "pos": [
        21044,
        21123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The custom API endpoint cannot be called using an HTTP method that has not been implemented in the server script, and a 405 (Method Not Allowed) error response is returned.",
      "pos": [
        21427,
        21599
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Separate permission levels can be assigned to each support HTTP method.",
      "pos": [
        21600,
        21671
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        21676,
        21741
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"api-return-xml\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Send and receive data as XML"
    },
    {
      "content": "When clients store and retrieve data, Mobile Services uses JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) to represent data in the message body.",
      "pos": [
        21743,
        21874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, there are scenarios where you instead want to use an XML payload.",
      "pos": [
        21875,
        21949
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, Windows Store apps have a built-in periodic notifications functionality that requires the service to emit XML.",
      "pos": [
        21950,
        22073
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Define a custom API that supports periodic notifications]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        22074,
        22159
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        22161,
        22264
      ],
      "content": "The following <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>OrderPizza<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> custom API function returns a simple XML document as the response payload:"
    },
    {
      "content": "This custom API function is invoked by an HTTP GET request to the following endpoint:",
      "pos": [
        22502,
        22587
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        22650,
        22728
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"get-api-user\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Work with users and headers in a custom API"
    },
    {
      "content": "In Azure Mobile Services, you can use an identity provider to authenticate users.",
      "pos": [
        22730,
        22811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Get started with authentication]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        22812,
        22872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When an authenticated user requests a custom API, Mobile Services uses the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">user object]</ept> to provide information about the user to custom API code.",
      "pos": [
        22873,
        23019
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">user object]</ept> is accessed from the user property of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">request object]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        23020,
        23097
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>userId<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property can be used to store and retrieve user-specific information.",
      "pos": [
        23098,
        23182
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        23185,
        23314
      ],
      "content": "The following <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>OrderPizza<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> custom API function sets the owner property of an item based on the userId of an authenticated user:"
    },
    {
      "content": "This custom API function is invoked by an HTTP POST request to the following endpoint:",
      "pos": [
        23757,
        23843
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        23904,
        24005
      ],
      "content": "You can also access a specific HTTP header from the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">request object]</ept>, as shown in the following code:"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        24191,
        24298
      ],
      "content": "This simple example reads a custom header named <ph id=\"ph1\">`my-custom-header`</ph>, then returns the value in the response."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        24303,
        24374
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"api-routes\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Define multiple routes in a custom API"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services enables you to define multiple paths, or routes, in a custom API.",
      "pos": [
        24376,
        24457
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, HTTP GET requests to the following URLs in a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>calculator<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> custom API will invoke an <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>add<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> or <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>subtract<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> function, respectively:",
      "pos": [
        24458,
        24604
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multiple routes are defined by exporting a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>register<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function, which is passed an <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>api<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> object (similar to the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p3\">express object in express.js]</ept>) that is used to register routes under the custom API endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        24724,
        24934
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following example implements the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>add<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>sub<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> methods in the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>calculator<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> custom API:",
      "pos": [
        24935,
        25033
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>api<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> object passed to the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>register<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> function exposes a function for each HTTP method (<bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>get<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>post<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>put<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>patch<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p7\">**</bpt>delete<ept id=\"p7\">**</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        25509,
        25656
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These functions register a route to a defined function for a specific HTTP method.",
      "pos": [
        25657,
        25739
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each function takes two parameters, the first is the route name and the second is the function registered to the route.",
      "pos": [
        25740,
        25859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The two routes in the above custom API example can be invoked by HTTP GET requests as follows (shown with the response):",
      "pos": [
        25862,
        25982
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        26165,
        26210
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"scheduler-scripts\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Job Scheduler"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services enables you to define server scripts that are executed either as jobs on a fixed schedule or on-demand from the Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        26212,
        26358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scheduled jobs are useful for performing periodic tasks such as cleaning-up table data and batch processing.",
      "pos": [
        26359,
        26467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Schedule jobs]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        26468,
        26510
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scripts that are registered to scheduled jobs have a main function with the same name as the scheduled job.",
      "pos": [
        26512,
        26619
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because a scheduled script is not invoked by an HTTP request, there is no context that can be passed by the server runtime and the function takes no parameters.",
      "pos": [
        26620,
        26780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like other kinds of scripts, you can have subroutine functions and require shared modules.",
      "pos": [
        26781,
        26871
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Source control, shared code, and helper functions].",
      "pos": [
        26872,
        26950
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        26955,
        27023
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"scheduler-scripts\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Define scheduled job scripts"
    },
    {
      "content": "A server script can be assigned to a job that's defined in the Mobile Services Scheduler.",
      "pos": [
        27025,
        27114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These scripts belong to the job and are executed according to the job schedule.",
      "pos": [
        27115,
        27194
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(You can also use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Management Portal]</ept> to run jobs on demand.) A script that defines a scheduled job has no parameters because Mobile Services doesn't pass it any data; it's executed as a regular JavaScript function and doesn't interact with Mobile Services directly.",
      "pos": [
        27195,
        27465
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You define scheduled jobs in one of the following ways:",
      "pos": [
        27468,
        27523
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        27528,
        27619
      ],
      "content": "In the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Management Portal<ept id=\"p1\">][Management Portal]</ept> in the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Script<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> tab in the scheduler:"
    },
    {
      "content": "![3][3]",
      "pos": [
        27625,
        27632
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        27638,
        27728
      ],
      "content": "For more information about how to do this, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Schedule backend jobs in Mobile Services]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "From the command prompt by using the Azure command line tool.",
      "pos": [
        27733,
        27794
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Using the command line tool].",
      "pos": [
        27795,
        27851
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>When you have source control enabled, you can edit scheduled job script files directly in the .\\service\\scheduler subfolder in your git repository.",
      "pos": [
        27854,
        28013
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [How to: Share code by using source control].",
      "pos": [
        28014,
        28085
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        28089,
        28164
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"shared-code\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Source control, shared code, and helper functions"
    },
    {
      "content": "This sections shows you how to leverage source control to add your own custom node.js modules, shared code and other code reuse strategies, including the following sections:",
      "pos": [
        28166,
        28339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview of leveraging shared code",
      "pos": [
        28344,
        28378
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Load Node.js modules]",
      "pos": [
        28408,
        28438
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Use helper functions]",
      "pos": [
        28441,
        28471
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Share code by using source control]",
      "pos": [
        28474,
        28518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Work with app settings]",
      "pos": [
        28521,
        28553
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        28559,
        28631
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"leverage-source-control\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Overview of leveraging shared code"
    },
    {
      "content": "Because Mobile Services uses Node.js on the server, your scripts already have access to the built-in Node.js modules.",
      "pos": [
        28633,
        28750
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also use source control to define your own modules or add other Node.js modules to your service.",
      "pos": [
        28751,
        28855
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        28857,
        28991
      ],
      "content": "The following are just some of the more useful modules that can be leveraged in your scripts by using the global <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>require<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function:"
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>azure<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Exposes the functionality of the Azure SDK for Node.js.",
      "pos": [
        28995,
        29061
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Azure SDK for Node.js]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29062,
        29116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>crypto<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Provides crypto functionality of OpenSSL.",
      "pos": [
        29120,
        29173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][crypto API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29174,
        29240
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>path<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Contains utilities for working with file paths.",
      "pos": [
        29243,
        29300
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][path API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29301,
        29365
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>querystring<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Contains utilities for working with query strings.",
      "pos": [
        29368,
        29435
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][querystring API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29436,
        29507
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>request<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Sends HTTP requests to external REST services, such as Twitter and Facebook.",
      "pos": [
        29510,
        29599
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Send HTTP request]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29600,
        29646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>sendgrid<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Sends email by using the Sendgrid email service in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        29649,
        29720
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Send email from Mobile Services with SendGrid]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29721,
        29795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>url<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Contains utilities to parse and resolve URLs.",
      "pos": [
        29798,
        29852
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][url API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        29853,
        29916
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>util<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Contains various utilities, such as string formatting and object type checking.",
      "pos": [
        29919,
        30008
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][util API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        30009,
        30073
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>zlib<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Exposes compression functionality, such as gzip and deflate.",
      "pos": [
        30077,
        30147
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Node.js documentation<ept id=\"p1\">][zlib API]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        30148,
        30212
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        30218,
        30281
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"modules-helper-functions\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Leverage modules"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services exposes a set of modules that scripts can load by using the global <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>require<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function.",
      "pos": [
        30283,
        30387
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, a script can require <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>request<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to make HTTP requests:",
      "pos": [
        30388,
        30456
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        30670,
        30753
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"shared-code-source-control\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Share code by using source control"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use source control with the Node.js package manager (npm) to control which modules are available to your mobile service.",
      "pos": [
        30755,
        30883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two ways to do this:",
      "pos": [
        30884,
        30914
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For modules that are published to and installed by npm, use the package.json file to declare which packages you want to be installed by your mobile service.",
      "pos": [
        30918,
        31074
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this way, your service always has access to the latest version of the required packages.",
      "pos": [
        31075,
        31166
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The package.json file lives in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`.\\service`</ph> directory.",
      "pos": [
        31167,
        31224
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Support for package.json in Azure Mobile Services]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        31225,
        31303
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For private or custom modules, you can use npm to manually install the module into the <ph id=\"ph1\">`.\\service\\node_modules`</ph> directory of your source control.",
      "pos": [
        31307,
        31452
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For an example of how to manually upload a module, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Leverage shared code and Node.js modules in your server scripts]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        31453,
        31574
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>When <ph id=\"ph2\">`node_modules`</ph> already exists in the directory hierarchy, NPM will create the <ph id=\"ph3\">`\\node-uuid`</ph> subdirectory there instead of creating a new <ph id=\"ph4\">`node_modules`</ph> in the repository.",
      "pos": [
        31581,
        31767
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, just delete the existing <ph id=\"ph1\">`node_modules`</ph> directory.",
      "pos": [
        31768,
        31832
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        31834,
        31983
      ],
      "content": "After you commit the package.json file or custom modules to the repository for your mobile service, use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>require<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to reference the modules by name."
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Modules that you specify in package.json or upload to your mobile service are only used in your server script code.",
      "pos": [
        31989,
        32117
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These modules are not used by the Mobile Services runtime.",
      "pos": [
        32118,
        32176
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        32181,
        32240
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"helper-functions\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Use helper functions"
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition to requiring modules, individual server scripts can include helper functions.",
      "pos": [
        32242,
        32331
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These are functions that are separate from the main function, which can be used to factor code in the script.",
      "pos": [
        32332,
        32441
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        32444,
        32584
      ],
      "content": "In the following example, a table script is registered to the insert operation, which includes the helper function <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>handleUnapprovedItem<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>:"
    },
    {
      "content": "In a script, helper functions must be declared after the main function.",
      "pos": [
        32923,
        32994
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must declare all variables in your script.",
      "pos": [
        32995,
        33041
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Undeclared variables cause an error.",
      "pos": [
        33042,
        33078
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Helper functions can also be defined once and shared between server scripts.",
      "pos": [
        33080,
        33156
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To share a function between scripts, functions must be exported and the script file must exist in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`.\\service\\shared\\`</ph> directory.",
      "pos": [
        33157,
        33289
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following is a template for how to export a shared function in a file <ph id=\"ph1\">`.\\services\\shared\\helpers.js`</ph>:",
      "pos": [
        33290,
        33395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can then use a function like this in a table operation script:",
      "pos": [
        33628,
        33694
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this example, you must pass both a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept> and a <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">user object]</ept> to the shared function.",
      "pos": [
        34030,
        34127
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is because shared scripts cannot access the global <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept>, and the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">user object]</ept> only exists in the context of a request.",
      "pos": [
        34128,
        34263
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Script files are uploaded to the shared directory either by using [source control][How to: Share code by using source control] or by using the [command line tool][Using the command line tool].",
      "pos": [
        34265,
        34457
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        34462,
        34519
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"app-settings\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Work with app settings"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services enables you to securely store values as app settings, which can be accessed by your server scripts at runtime.",
      "pos": [
        34521,
        34647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you add data to the app settings of your mobile service, the name/value pairs are stored encrypted and you can access them in your server scripts without hard-coding them in the script file.",
      "pos": [
        34649,
        34844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">App settings]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        34845,
        34886
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        34888,
        34989
      ],
      "content": "The following custom API example uses the supplied <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">service object]</ept> to retrieve an app setting value."
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code uses the configuration module to retrieve Twitter access token values, stored in app settings, that are used in a scheduled job script:",
      "pos": [
        35306,
        35460
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that this code also retrieves Twitter consumer key values stored in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Identity<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab in the portal.",
      "pos": [
        35947,
        36055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>config object<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is not available in table operation and scheduled job scripts, you must require the configuration module to access app settings.",
      "pos": [
        36056,
        36212
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a complete example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Schedule backend jobs in Mobile Services]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        36213,
        36284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"command-prompt\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Using the command line tool",
      "pos": [
        36290,
        36346
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Mobile Services, you can create, modify, and delete server scripts by using the Azure command line tool.",
      "pos": [
        36353,
        36460
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before uploading your scripts, make sure that you are using the following directory structure:",
      "pos": [
        36461,
        36555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![4][4]",
      "pos": [
        36557,
        36564
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that this directory structure is the same as the git repository when using source control.",
      "pos": [
        36566,
        36661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When uploading script files from the command line tool, you must first navigate to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`.\\services\\`</ph> directory.",
      "pos": [
        36664,
        36775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following command uploads a script named <ph id=\"ph1\">`todoitem.insert.js`</ph> from the <ph id=\"ph2\">`table`</ph> subdirectory:",
      "pos": [
        36776,
        36872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following command returns information about every script file maintained in your mobile service:",
      "pos": [
        37051,
        37151
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        38568,
        38637
      ],
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Commands to manage Azure Mobile Services]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        38642,
        38695
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"working-with-tables\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Working with tables"
    },
    {
      "content": "This section details strategies for working directly with SQL Database table data, including the following sections:",
      "pos": [
        38697,
        38813
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview of working with tables",
      "pos": [
        38818,
        38849
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Access tables from scripts]",
      "pos": [
        38871,
        38907
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Perform Bulk Inserts]",
      "pos": [
        38910,
        38940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[How to: Map JSON types to database types]",
      "pos": [
        38943,
        38985
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "[Using Transact-SQL to access tables]",
      "pos": [
        38988,
        39025
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        39030,
        39091
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"overview-tables\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Overview of working with tables"
    },
    {
      "content": "Many scenarios in Mobile Services require server scripts to access tables in the database.",
      "pos": [
        39093,
        39183
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example.",
      "pos": [
        39184,
        39196
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "because Mobile Services does not preserve state between script executions, any data that needs to be persisted between script executions must be stored in tables.",
      "pos": [
        39197,
        39359
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might also want to examine entries in a permissions table or store audit data instead of just writing to the log, where data has a limited duration and cannot be accessed programmatically.",
      "pos": [
        39360,
        39552
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services has two ways of accessing tables, either by using a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">table object]</ept> proxy or by composing Transact-SQL queries using the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">mssql object]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        39555,
        39706
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">table object]</ept> makes it easy to access table data from your sever script code, but the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">mssql object]</ept> supports more complex data operations and provides the most flexibility.",
      "pos": [
        39707,
        39885
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        39891,
        39953
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"access-tables\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Access tables from scripts"
    },
    {
      "content": "The easiest way to access tables from your script is by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        39955,
        40037
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>getTable<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> function returns a <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">table object]</ept> instance that's a proxy for accessing the requested table.",
      "pos": [
        40038,
        40147
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can then call functions on the proxy to access and change data.",
      "pos": [
        40148,
        40215
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scripts registered to both table operations and scheduled jobs can access the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept> as a global object.",
      "pos": [
        40218,
        40331
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This line of code gets a proxy for the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>TodoItems<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> table from the global <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">tables object]</ept>:",
      "pos": [
        40332,
        40421
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Custom API scripts can access the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept> from the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>service<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph> property of the supplied <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">request object]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        40484,
        40610
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This line of code gets <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept> from the request:",
      "pos": [
        40611,
        40667
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Shared functions cannot access the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>tables<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> object directly.",
      "pos": [
        40746,
        40821
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a shared function, you must pass the tables object to the function.",
      "pos": [
        40822,
        40892
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once you have a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">table object]</ept>, you can call one or more table operation functions: insert, update, delete or read.",
      "pos": [
        40894,
        41009
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This example reads user permissions from a permissions table:",
      "pos": [
        41010,
        41071
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        41794,
        41861
      ],
      "content": "The next example writes auditing information to an <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>audit<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> table:"
    },
    {
      "content": "A final example is in the code sample here: [How to: Access custom parameters][How to: Add custom parameters].",
      "pos": [
        42514,
        42624
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        42629,
        42684
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"bulk-inserts\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Perform Bulk Inserts"
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>for<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> or <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>while<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> loop to directly insert a large number of items (1000, for example) into a  table , you may encounter a SQL connection limit that causes some of the inserts to fail.",
      "pos": [
        42686,
        42885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your request may never complete or it may return a HTTP 500 Internal Server Error.",
      "pos": [
        42886,
        42968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To avoid this problem, you can insert the items in batches of 10 or so.",
      "pos": [
        42970,
        43041
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the first batch is inserted, submit the next batch, and so on.",
      "pos": [
        43042,
        43110
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By using the following script, you can set the size of a batch of records to insert in parallel.",
      "pos": [
        43112,
        43208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We recomend that you keep the number of records small.",
      "pos": [
        43209,
        43263
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The function <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>insertItems<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> calls itself recursively when an async insert batch has completed.",
      "pos": [
        43264,
        43359
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The for loop at the end inserts one record at a time, and calls <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>insertComplete<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> on success and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>errorHandler<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> on error.",
      "pos": [
        43360,
        43484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>insertComplete<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  controls whether <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>insertItems<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> will be called recursively for the next batch, or whether the job is done and the script should exit.",
      "pos": [
        43485,
        43639
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The entire code sample, and accompanying discussion, can be found in this <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>blog posting<ept id=\"p1\">](http://blogs.msdn.com/b/jpsanders/archive/2013/03/20/server-script-to-insert-table-items-in-windows-azure-mobile-services.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        45225,
        45442
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use this code, you can adapt it to your specific situation, and thoroughly test it.",
      "pos": [
        45443,
        45533
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        45538,
        45603
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"JSON-types\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Map JSON types to database types"
    },
    {
      "content": "The collections of data types on the client and in a Mobile Services database table are different.",
      "pos": [
        45605,
        45703
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sometimes they map easily to one another, and other times they don't.",
      "pos": [
        45704,
        45773
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services performs a number of type transformations in the mapping:",
      "pos": [
        45774,
        45847
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The client language-specific types are serialized into JSON.",
      "pos": [
        45851,
        45911
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The JSON representation is translated into JavaScript before it appears in server scripts.",
      "pos": [
        45914,
        46004
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        46007,
        46106
      ],
      "content": "The JavaScript data types are converted to SQL database types when saved using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "The transformation from client schema into JSON varies across platforms.",
      "pos": [
        46108,
        46180
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "JSON.NET is used in Windows Store and Windows Phone clients.",
      "pos": [
        46182,
        46242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Android client uses the gson library.",
      "pos": [
        46243,
        46284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The iOS client uses the NSJSONSerialization class.",
      "pos": [
        46286,
        46336
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default serialization behavior of each of these libraries is used, except that date objects are converted to JSON strings that contain the date that's encoded by using ISO 8601.",
      "pos": [
        46337,
        46518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you are writing server scripts that use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">insert]</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">update]</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p3\">read]</ept> or <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p4\">delete]</ept> functions, you can access the JavaScript representation of your data.",
      "pos": [
        46520,
        46673
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services uses the Node.js's deserialization function (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>JSON.parse<ept id=\"p1\">](http://es5.github.io/#x15.12)</ept>) to transform JSON on the wire into JavaScript objects.",
      "pos": [
        46674,
        46833
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However Mobile Services does  a transformation to extract <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Date<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> objects from ISO 8601 strings.",
      "pos": [
        46834,
        46931
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">tables object]</ept> or the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">mssql object]</ept>, or just let your table scripts execute, the deserialized JavaScript objects are inserted into your SQL database.",
      "pos": [
        46933,
        47101
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In that process, object properties are mapped to T-SQL types:",
      "pos": [
        47102,
        47163
      ]
