      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        50175,
        50225
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"joins\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Join relational tables"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can join two tables by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>query<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> method of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">mssql object]</ept> to pass in the TSQL code that implements the join.",
      "pos": [
        50227,
        50353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let's assume we have some items in our <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ToDoItem<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> table and each item in the table has a <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>priority<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> property, which corresponds to a column in the table.",
      "pos": [
        50354,
        50511
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An item may look like this:",
      "pos": [
        50512,
        50539
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let's also assume we have an additional table called <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Priority<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> with rows that contain a priority <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>number<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> and a text <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>description<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        50610,
        50748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the priority number 1 might have the description of \"Critical\", with the object looking as follows:",
      "pos": [
        50749,
        50861
      ]
    },
    {
